A certain nebula is enclosing a roughly spherical area with volume of `a`×1057 cm3, and there are 1000 hydrogen atoms per cm3. Calculate the approximate number of hydrogen atoms in the nebula.

Enter the number in scientific notation and with two digits past the decimal point; if the answer was 1.23×1045 you would type 1.23*10^45

1 light-year = 1018 cm

A certain nebula is enclosing a roughly spherical area with volume of `a`×1057 cm3, and there are 1000 hydrogen atoms per cm3. How many stars like our Sun could be formed from this nebula? Note, our Sun is composed of 1.00×1057 hydrogen atoms. 

Do not enter the answer in scientific notation.
